  <h1>Machine-readable surfaces for agents and authoring tools</h1>
  <p>
    Aihio’s docs are only one consumer of the generated schema. The same build also emits a prompt fragment,
    a structured linter, and a local MCP server for component discovery and markup validation.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="docs-feature-grid">
  <div class="docs-feature-card">
    <h3><code>dist/schema.json</code></h3>
    <p>Human-readable schema bundle containing components, intents, patterns, a11y contracts, examples, and counterexamples.</p>
    <pre class="docs-code"><code>import schema from 'aihio/schema';</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="docs-feature-card">
    <h3><code>aihio/lint</code></h3>
    <p>Structured schema-backed HTML validation that returns machine-consumable issues.</p>
    <pre class="docs-code"><code>import { lintMarkup } from 'aihio/lint';

const result = lintMarkup('&lt;aihio-button size="icon"&gt;&lt;/aihio-button&gt;');</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="docs-feature-card">
    <h3><code>aihio/prompt</code></h3>
    <p>Canonical prompt fragment summarizing components, patterns, hard rules, and the token vocabulary.</p>
    <pre class="docs-code"><code>import prompt from 'aihio/prompt';</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="docs-feature-card">
    <h3><code>aihio-mcp</code></h3>
    <p>Local stdio MCP server exposing <code>describe</code> and <code>lint</code> tools for clients that can launch subprocesses.</p>
    <pre class="docs-code"><code>{
  "mcpServers": {
    "aihio": {
      "command": "aihio-mcp"
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
  </div>
</section>
